 ('154', '88', '2', '1', 'en_us', '4', '', '{\"typeId\":\"2\",\"authorId\":\"1\",\"title\":\"Bottling Pinko Pallino, March 16th, 2015\",\"slug\":\"pinko-pallino-getting-bottled\",\"postDate\":1429023000,\"expiryDate\":null,\"enabled\":1,\"fields\":{\"1\":\"<p>Getting ready for Spring and Summer? so what do we do? Bottle our Ros\\u00e9! Monday morning we bottled Pinko Pallino. Because 2014 was such a difficult year, we ended up with little ros\\u00e9. We stored it in the smaller vat (with the addition of the cooling plate to maintain temperature at below 12 degrees celcius). This year we had a lot of fun making Pinko Pallino because we ended doing a blend of Gigio\' \\\"bled off juice\\\" and early harvest grapes specifically for ros\\u00e9 with its own white wine like Vinification (meaning that you press the bunches right away). Our bottling operation is still artisanal, but it works! Juice flows from the vat to a small filter to the bottling machine into the bottles which then are immediately corked with the remaining air getting pumped out. We then let the bottles rest 24 hours standing up, to allow the corks to expand and after that they\'re moved to our temperature controlled cellar to rest on their sides until we ship out. We did get to taste it though, yum !!!!<\\/p><p><img style=\\\"width: 448px; height: 251.57px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/getting-ready-to-bottle.jpg#asset:85:url\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\">  <\\/p><p><img style=\\\"width: 335px; height: 189.56px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/enzo-manning-the-bottling-machine.jpg#asset:86:url\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\">   <img style=\\\"width: 106px; height: 188.78px;\\\" src=\\\"http:\\/\\/www.poggiolanoce.com\\/images\\/pages\\/Pinko-Pallino-bottled-and-corked.jpg#asset:87:url\\\" unselectable=\\\"on\\\"><\\/p>\",\"25\":\"\",\"2\":\"\"}}', '2015-04-14 17:20:52', '2015-04-14 17:20:52', '80b61749-154a-4b20-a80c-5147fb45f69d'),
