 ('95', 'field', '1', 'en_us', ' back to pruning couple of weeks ago we mentioned that these cold winter months were spent pruning the vines and yes but today let s delve into the world of pruning a bit more here we have our teroldego vines which we pruned differently than the sangiovese for the teroldego we used a different pruning technique called double guyot basically we prune or train the vines to manage their world their environment the different techniques allow us to deal with leaf to fruit ratios light vs shade air movement canopy disease protection and of course yield in the bulk of the vineyard where sangiovese grows we re doing spur pruning simply put the cordon or main branch of the vine has a bunch of spurs mushroom like bumps which each generate 2 fruiting canes the thinner branches which produce the grape bunches when we prune we cut off completely the fruiting cane furthest away from the spur and shorten the one closest to the spur thus allowing next year s spur to generate 2 new fruiting canes well that s the theory with the teroldego we did double guyot pruning the main difference with the guyot system is that it keeps a 2 year old cane to allow it to generate more fruiting canes and thus potentially yield more fruit it s used for less vigorous vine varieties to help yields so at pruning we cut off the 2 year old cane and at the spur the cane closest to the cordon is cut above two nodes while the cane furthest away is shortened that cane will become next year s two year old cane only tweak is us doing double or bilateral meaning that we allow for two 2 year old canes one on each side that s the world of vine pruning in the winter time at la noce '),
